WEBVTT

00:04.091 --> 00:06.789
It wouldn't be enough
to cover the entire recall,

00:06.789 --> 00:07.920
but we could stop
using the corporate jets

00:07.920 --> 00:09.531
for non-company business.

00:09.531 --> 00:10.880
We do that now?

00:10.880 --> 00:13.665
Well, some people take
"market research" trips

00:13.665 --> 00:14.971
to every Mardi Gras.

00:14.971 --> 00:17.060
Uh, bullying?
Anyone want to step in here?

00:17.060 --> 00:18.583
Mm-mm.

00:18.583 --> 00:19.671
Couldn't we just charge,
like, 50 bucks more a car?

00:19.671 --> 00:20.759
No one would notice.

00:20.759 --> 00:21.934
Yes, people famously
don't haggle

00:21.934 --> 00:23.501
over the prices of their cars.

00:23.501 --> 00:24.502
None of that is big enough.

00:24.502 --> 00:26.287
We have been at this for hours,

00:26.287 --> 00:28.332
and all we've decided
is where to order lunch.

00:28.332 --> 00:29.899
We should have spent
more time on that.

00:29.899 --> 00:31.074
This sandwich dry as hell.

00:31.074 --> 00:32.467
Look, I hate to be
the one to say it,

00:32.467 --> 00:34.469
but we all know
what needs to be done.

00:34.469 --> 00:36.906
We have to close a factory.

00:36.906 --> 00:38.603
I said I hate to say it,
all right?

00:38.603 --> 00:39.691
That absolves me.

00:39.691 --> 00:40.910
I really don't want
to do that.

00:40.910 --> 00:42.129
None of us do, but sometimes

00:42.129 --> 00:43.739
you have to cut off the hand
to save the arm.

00:43.739 --> 00:45.088
Ah, like zombies.

00:45.088 --> 00:46.307
Why are factory workers
always the first ones

00:46.307 --> 00:47.525
on the chopping block?
- Mm.

00:47.525 --> 00:48.744
Nothing ever seems
to touch the people

00:48.744 --> 00:50.006
with the cushy office jobs.

00:50.006 --> 00:51.703
You know what?
That is not a bad point.

00:51.703 --> 00:53.270
I mean, it'd be a bloodbath
up here,

00:53.270 --> 00:55.272
but downsizing executives
would get us a lot more savings

00:55.272 --> 00:56.534
with fewer bodies.

00:56.534 --> 00:57.535
No, I wasn't suggesting
that we actually--

00:57.535 --> 00:58.754
You know, I hate to say it,

00:58.754 --> 01:00.147
but we wouldn't have to
cut production

01:00.147 --> 01:01.800
if we went with
Jack's Red Wedding thing.

01:01.800 --> 01:03.106
Okay, Red Wedding is not
what I was actually saying.

01:03.106 --> 01:04.368
- We shouldn't fire anyone.
- Exactly.

01:04.368 --> 01:05.674
But if we have to,

01:05.674 --> 01:07.154
we would get less blowback
with Jack's idea.

01:07.154 --> 01:08.372
And then we could
loosen restrictions

01:08.372 --> 01:09.460
on the corporate jet, right?

01:09.460 --> 01:11.027
What is wrong with you,
Wesley?

01:11.027 --> 01:12.898
These people 'bout to be
homeless and lose their jobs,

01:12.898 --> 01:14.552
and you're worried about
seeing boobs for free?

01:14.552 --> 01:17.207
It's not free.
It's like a barter economy.

01:17.207 --> 01:18.426
Okay, fine.
We'll go with Jack's idea.

01:18.426 --> 01:19.731
Let' start
with every department,

01:19.731 --> 01:20.863
letting one executive go,

01:20.863 --> 01:22.256
and then we'll reassess
from there.

01:22.256 --> 01:25.128
Oh, God. They have no idea
what's coming.

01:25.128 --> 01:26.390
Stop staring.
You're making it obvious.

01:26.390 --> 01:27.522
Pretend I said something inspiring.

01:27.522 --> 01:29.654
Clap, clap, clap, clap.
- Oh, bravo.

01:29.654 --> 01:31.265
But wait, wait, wait,
no, no, no, no.

01:31.265 --> 01:33.528
It looks like we decided to
fire them and then applauded.

01:33.528 --> 01:34.616
Just close the blinds;
close the blinds.

01:34.616 --> 01:36.096
Yes. On it.
Closing the blinds.

01:37.401 --> 01:38.924
<i>♪ Bom bom
bom-bom-bom-bom-bom ♪</i>

01:38.924 --> 01:41.449
