02:55.044 --> 02:56.654
times, like, 20,000 employees,

02:56.654 --> 02:58.003
who knows how much
that would save?

02:58.003 --> 02:59.222
$2,000.

02:59.222 --> 03:01.006
Did you just do that
in your head?

03:01.006 --> 03:02.399
I mean, I guess we do
use a lot of stuff

03:02.399 --> 03:03.792
that we actually don't need.

03:03.792 --> 03:05.489
Like, why does everybody
have tape on their desk?

03:05.489 --> 03:06.969
We're not doing arts and crafts
up in here.

03:06.969 --> 03:08.275
Yeah.

03:08.275 --> 03:09.928
I mean, you cut some pens;
you cut some tape.

03:09.928 --> 03:12.757
- That's, like, pure savings.
- Yeah.

03:12.757 --> 03:14.237
Let's go check out
the supply room.

03:14.237 --> 03:17.414
Ooh, yeah.
Uh, don't worry, guys.

03:17.414 --> 03:20.461
This mismatched pair of ragtags
is gonna save your jobs.

03:20.461 --> 03:22.158
And in the process,

03:22.158 --> 03:25.553
we just may find out we have
more in common than we think.

03:25.553 --> 03:27.511
What does he mean
save our jobs?

03:27.511 --> 03:30.035
Anyone know what he means
by that?

03:30.035 --> 03:31.689
Hey, Katherine.

03:31.689 --> 03:33.822
"Ticker Tape" on CNBC wants to
interview you this afternoon.

03:33.822 --> 03:34.953
- Today?
- Mm.

03:34.953 --> 03:36.216
On the day of these layoffs?
Pass.

03:36.216 --> 03:37.521
I mean, that would be like

03:37.521 --> 03:39.871
taking a victory lap
at a euthanasia party.

03:39.871 --> 03:40.872
- Mm.
- Yeah.

03:40.872 --> 03:42.265
Not a perfect metaphor.

03:42.265 --> 03:43.658
But the point is,
terrible timing.

03:43.658 --> 03:45.442
Right, yeah,
but I was also thinking

03:45.442 --> 03:47.096
maybe it's perfect timing.
- Hmm?

03:47.096 --> 03:50.142
It shows that we're taking
hard actions to cut costs,

03:50.142 --> 03:52.797
which Wall Street will love,
but we're doing it by

03:52.797 --> 03:55.409
letting go of executives
instead of blue-collar workers,

03:55.409 --> 03:57.237
which, I mean,
Main Street will love.

03:57.237 --> 03:58.368
- Yeah.
- Oh, right?

03:58.368 --> 03:59.587
Interesting.
Love from both streets.

03:59.587 --> 04:00.936
I mean, that's
all the streets there are.

04:00.936 --> 04:02.285
Yeah.

04:02.285 --> 04:04.287
Katherine Hastings,
savior of the underlings.

04:04.287 --> 04:06.246
Maybe we could
workshop the phrasing.

04:06.246 --> 04:07.812
Savior of the peons?

04:07.812 --> 04:09.466
Uh, just workers.

04:09.466 --> 04:11.947
Eh, doesn't really pop.
I'll play with it.

04:11.947 --> 04:13.340
Right.

04:13.340 --> 04:14.471
So the first few pages

04:14.471 --> 04:15.951
are just
the standard layoff script,

04:15.951 --> 04:19.259
and the rest is a list
of acceptable legal responses

04:19.259 --> 04:20.521
to anything they may say
to you.

04:20.521 --> 04:22.479
So I'm just supposed
to read this to them?

04:22.479 --> 04:23.741
Seems a little heartless.

04:23.741 --> 04:25.047
Precisely, yeah.
Just get through it

04:25.047 --> 04:27.136
with an emotionless,
surgical precision.

04:27.136 --> 04:29.747
You know, like a child
of an acrimonious divorce

04:29.747 --> 04:31.314
dissecting a backyard squirrel.

04:31.314 --> 04:33.751
Please, Jack.
There's an art to this.

04:33.751 --> 04:36.014
People don't want a robot.
They want to be heard.

04:36.014 --> 04:38.147
They want to be seen.
- Just stick to the script.

04:38.147 --> 04:39.322
Stick to the script,

04:39.322 --> 04:41.846
but breathe some life into it, hmm?

04:41.846 --> 04:43.239
Connect with your
scene partner.

04:43.239 --> 04:45.110
- My scene partner?
- Let's say I'm firing you.

04:45.110 --> 04:48.070
I gotta ask myself, "What
do I think makes Jack tick?"

04:48.070 --> 04:50.768
So while my mouth may be
going through the motions

04:50.768 --> 04:53.467
and saying the words,
my mind is thinking,

04:53.467 --> 04:55.599
"Light beer, bouncing breasts,

04:55.599 --> 04:57.645
he probably ain't
cracked a book in ages."

04:57.645 --> 05:00.125
- Little condescending, but--
- It's art, Jack.

05:00.125 --> 05:02.780
It's supposed to make you
feel uncomfortable.

05:02.780 --> 05:05.435
Yeah, I mean, you have
to admit we do love breasts.

05:05.435 --> 05:06.828
He's not wrong about that.

05:06.828 --> 05:08.308
Okay, but what do I do
if he, like,

05:08.308 --> 05:10.353
starts freaking out screaming,
"I'm gonna kill myself,"

05:10.353 --> 05:12.573
